  "prompt": "What is the difference between gypsum and marble?",
  "response": "Gypsum and marble are both minerals that are used in various applications, but they differ significantly in composition, properties, and uses.\n\n**Gypsum:**\n1. **Chemical Composition:** Gypsum is a sulfate mineral composed mainly of calcium sulfate dihydrate (CaSO\u2084\u00b72H\u2082O).\n2. **Physical Properties:**\n   - **Hardness:** It is relatively soft with a Mohs hardness of around 2.\n   - **Appearance:** Gypsum is typically white or colorless, although it can also occur in shades of grey, yellow, red, brown, or pink due to impurities.\n   - **Crystal Form:** It often forms in well-defined crystals and can be transparent or translucent.\n3. **Uses:** Gypsum is widely used in the construction industry, primarily to manufacture drywall and plaster. It is also used in cement production, soil conditioning, and as a modeling material.\n\n**Marble:**\n1. **Chemical Composition:** Marble is a metamorphic rock primarily composed of recrystallized carbonate minerals, most commonly calcite (CaCO\u2083) or dolomite (CaMg(CO\u2083)\u2082).\n2. **Physical Properties:**\n   - **Hardness:** Marble has a Mohs hardness of around 3 to 4, making it harder than gypsum but still relatively soft compared to other stones like granite.\n   - **Appearance:** Marble is known for its aesthetic appeal with varied colors and veining patterns, depending on the impurities and mineral content. Common colors include white, black, grey, green, pink, and many more.\n3. **Uses:** Marble is extensively used in architecture and sculpture. It is popular for flooring, countertops, wall cladding, and decorative purposes due to its beauty and ability to be polished to a high sheen. It is also used in the production of dimension stone and in the manufacture of lime.\n\nIn summary, while both gypsum and marble are naturally occurring materials, gypsum is a softer mineral primarily used in construction, and marble is a harder, aesthetically pleasing stone used prominently in decorative and architectural applications.",
